    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_32819625" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/32819625" />
    <a title="Melissa Rudder" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/824216-melissa-rudder"><img alt="Melissa Rudder" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1201213962p2/824216.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/32819625?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melissa Rudder" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melissa Rudder" href="/user/show/824216-melissa-rudder">Melissa Rudder</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer32819625" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11523762975409212411">Despite the endearing jovial triviality of Niccolo Machiavelli’s <i>Mandragola</i>, I can’t say I’m too impressed.<br/><br/>In his prologue to the play—a feature often used as a sort of apology (no, not the “I’m sorry” type)—Machiavelli amuses me with his assessment of the play and stated motive:<br/><br/>	And if the theme we offer,<br/>	Being so light, does not befit<br/>	A man who wishes to seem grave and wise,	<br/>	Forgive him on this ground: he tries his wit<br/>	With trifles, hoping thus to minimize<br/>	The ordeal of a life full of concern</span>
  <span id="freeText11523762975409212411" style="display:none">Despite the endearing jovial triviality of Niccolo Machiavelli’s <i>Mandragola</i>, I can’t say I’m too impressed.<br /><br />In his prologue to the play—a feature often used as a sort of apology (no, not the “I’m sorry” type)—Machiavelli amuses me with his assessment of the play and stated motive:<br /><br />	And if the theme we offer,<br />	Being so light, does not befit<br />	A man who wishes to seem grave and wise,	<br />	Forgive him on this ground: he tries his wit<br />	With trifles, hoping thus to minimize<br />	The ordeal of a life full of concern<br /><br />As I began to read the story and stumbled upon this playful verse, I looked forward to a humorous play about nothing, but I was very much disappointed.<br /><br />Before I get to my problem with the play, however, I have to interject with a bit about the characters. Many plays that I’ve read for this course I’m in (all the plays I’ve reviewed up to this point) have seemed to lack characterization, prepared to rely on the clutch of the players to imbue the subjects with personality, but I feel like Machiavelli prepares a nice foundation for players to expand on, while definitely not restricting their creativity. My favorite character was Messer Nicia, who was just about as dense as they come. The writing for him was extremely humorous and would be exponentially improved onstage, with the right actor, of course. Also to note is the rather fascinating Machiavellian characteristics of the characters. Despite the unique quality of each, it can be argued for pretty much any character that he or she is doing anything to achieve his or her (self-centered) goal. This leads to doubt about the frivolous nature of the plot, yet its simplistic presentation still encourages me to adopt the “simple play” opinion, regardless of its challenged accuracy. <br /><br />Okay, I hate to pull this again, but I have to whip out a feminist critique. I was never really concerned with feminist issues (I hold great disdain for , for instance) until I began reading classic plays (although I have to correct myself: this is a neoclassic play from the Italian Renaissance). But, anyway, Machiavelli claims that he’s trying his wit “with trifles,” and I beg to differ. The play is about a man who forces his wife to have sex with another man. And at the end, the wife decides that it must be God’s will that she be with the second man, who has conjured this great scheme to force her to sleep with him. You should be able to pick up an aggravated tone from my text. I mean, I don’t know about you, but I’m insulted. “No! I’m too virtuous to have sex with another man! Don’t make me… [later]… Wow, that was good. I was forced to do this against my will—my dignity and honor was discarded—but God must have wanted it that way. Take me now.” Ugh.<br /><br />Machiavelli has a simplistic but amicable style, but he kills it with his plot. And while I can accept crap like this from Shakespeare, I just don’t think it’s worth it from him.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11523762975409212411" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

