    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_464229683" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/464229683" />
    <a title="Otto Lehto" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4024817-otto-lehto"><img alt="Otto Lehto" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349907515p2/4024817.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/464229683?book_show_action=true">Nov 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Otto Lehto" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Otto Lehto" href="/user/show/4024817-otto-lehto">Otto Lehto</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer464229683" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer881088645105089204">A wonderful comedy from the master of early &quot;realist&quot; political philosophy. <br/><br/>&quot;Mandragola&quot; portrays, in hindsight, some rather &quot;Machiavellian&quot; themes, but in the context of aristocratic love intrigue rather than in the political context - war, conquest, power and conspiracy - of the Machiavelli of &quot;The Prince.&quot;<br/><br/>This play truly hits home the truth that &quot;all&apos;s fair in love and war&quot; - and who better the man to act as our guide than Machiavelli (the greatest exemplar of the &quot;all&apos;s fair&quot; doctrine of mor</span>
  <span id="freeText881088645105089204" style="display:none">A wonderful comedy from the master of early "realist" political philosophy. <br /><br />"Mandragola" portrays, in hindsight, some rather "Machiavellian" themes, but in the context of aristocratic love intrigue rather than in the political context - war, conquest, power and conspiracy - of the Machiavelli of "The Prince."<br /><br />This play truly hits home the truth that "all's fair in love and war" - and who better the man to act as our guide than Machiavelli (the greatest exemplar of the "all's fair" doctrine of morality)? <br /><br />It's curious that there aren't that many contemporary performances of Mandragola, that I know of, which is a shame, because there's great potential here for mass-appealing raunchiness. Teenagers and decadent liberals ought to love this piece. It would go down well on Broadway or late night TV. Low-brow humour and references to the male organ abound in Mandragola. <br /><br />PS. There is an interesting connection (although my etymological dictionary doesn't believe in it) between the Latin words for "virtue" - virtus - and "penis" - virga. Machiavelli is an expert on both. Both words relate to "man" - vir.<br /><br />To analyze the relationship between Mandragola and the non-fiction side of Machiavelli's oeuvre is perfectly possible, but that would be spoiling the plot, although the play can be enjoyed as merely harmless entertainment as well. But suffice it to say that the gist of the plot is distinctly Machiavellian!<br /><br />Reading the play made me appreciate the unity behind Machiavelli's double role as playwright and political theorist: to understand love is to understand politics. Love requires stratagems that would make an honest man blush. The same goes for politics. There is a great deal in common between the advice given (in the guise of non-fiction) to the power-hungry Prince and the advice given (in the guise of fiction) to the love-hungry Aristocrat. Machiavelli advices, in either case: "do what you must to gain what you desire!"<br /><br />The only question remains: should you TAKE that advice... it's a devil's bargain. But a damn tempting bargain! Ask yourself: are you a Faust or an Angel?</span>
  <a data-text-id="881088645105089204" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


