<div id="review_594372573" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/594372573" />
    <a title="Roux Stellarsphyr" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19567682-roux-stellarsphyr"><img alt="Roux Stellarsphyr" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615843260p2/19567682.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/594372573?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roux Stellarsphyr" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roux Stellarsphyr" href="/user/show/19567682-roux-stellarsphyr">Roux Stellarsphyr</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer594372573" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3384204494222143464">Machiavelli is known, of course, for his political treatises _The Discourses on Livy_ and _The Prince_. However, Mandragola (or, The Mandrake Root) is not political in nature (though some have argued it can be read that way).<br/><br/>Definitely funny and a play that Machiavelli claimed &apos;held up a mirror to the private life,&apos; Mandragola is a quick read and a necessary one for the student of Machiavelli.</span>
  <span id="freeText3384204494222143464" style="display:none">Machiavelli is known, of course, for his political treatises _The Discourses on Livy_ and _The Prince_. However, Mandragola (or, The Mandrake Root) is not political in nature (though some have argued it can be read that way).<br /><br />Definitely funny and a play that Machiavelli claimed 'held up a mirror to the private life,' Mandragola is a quick read and a necessary one for the student of Machiavelli.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3384204494222143464" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


