<div id="review_1646760098" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1646760098" />
    <a title="Chris" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15405911-chris"><img alt="Chris" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1355283988p2/15405911.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1646760098?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris" href="/user/show/15405911-chris">Chris</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1646760098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12017447063663033757">Basically, a Machiavellian farce. In some ways, The Prince but in (&quot;romantic&quot;) comedy garb, and exploring not political but social relationships and notions of power. It will outrage feminists (and rightfully so) but at the risk of sounding like an apologist, it should be put into its proper context. All I really ask of ancient works and all supposed &quot;classics&quot; is to make me think. </span>
  <span id="freeText12017447063663033757" style="display:none">Basically, a Machiavellian farce. In some ways, The Prince but in ("romantic") comedy garb, and exploring not political but social relationships and notions of power. It will outrage feminists (and rightfully so) but at the risk of sounding like an apologist, it should be put into its proper context. All I really ask of ancient works and all supposed "classics" is to make me think. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12017447063663033757" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


